"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631150","Department of Health","false","2016-11-14","<p>The information in the attached table shows the number of unplanned accident and emergency attendances with a Patient Group category of Deliberate self-harm for the whole of England and for the years 2009-10 to 2014-15. This is not a count of individual patients as the same person may have attended an Emergency Department on more than one occasion.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-11-14T16:01:40.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631150/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631150/answer","PQ51973 table1.xlsx","PQ51973 table1.xlsx","PQ51973 table","PQ51973 table","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631150/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-07","Accident and Emergency Departments: Self-harm","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many people attended accident and emergency due to intentional self-harm by gender and age group in each of the last six years.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","51973"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631151","Department of Health","false","2016-11-14","<p>The information in the attached table shows the number of unplanned accident and emergency attendances with a primary diagnosis of psychiatric conditions by five-year age group and gender, for the whole of England and for the years 2009-10 to 2014-15. This is not a count of individual patients as the same person may have attended an Emergency Department on more than one occasion.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-11-14T17:38:49.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631151/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631151/answer","PQ51974 table1.xlsx","PQ51974 table1.xlsx","PQ51974 table1","PQ51974 table1","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631151/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-07","Accident and Emergency Departments: Mental Illness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many people attended accident and emergency with a primary diagnosis of a mental health condition by type of mental health condition, gender and age group in each of the last six years.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","51974"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631152","Department of Health","false","2016-11-14","<p>The table below provides the number of patients where a primary diagnosis of a psychiatric condition or an accident and emergency (A&amp;E) patient group of deliberate self-harm, where the patient reattended within seven days or at any time during the year, for the years 2009-10 to 2014-15. It is possible for a patient to have both a psychiatric diagnosis and self-harm recorded on the same attendance. As a result, one attendance can be recorded twice within the data below.</p><p> </p><p>Activity in English National Health Service Hospitals and English NHS commissioned activity in the independent sector</p><p> </p><p>Primary diagnosis of a psychiatric condition and A&amp;E patient group of deliberate self-harm</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Re-attendance within 0-7 days</p></td><td><p>Re-attendance during the year</p></td><td><p>Re-attendance within 0-7 days</p></td><td><p>Re-attendance during the year</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009-10</p></td><td><p>3,966</p></td><td><p>21,715</p></td><td><p>4,319</p></td><td><p>25,168</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>4,443</p></td><td><p>22,597</p></td><td><p>4,589</p></td><td><p>25,486</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>5,520</p></td><td><p>25,716</p></td><td><p>4,902</p></td><td><p>25,736</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>5,814</p></td><td><p>25,854</p></td><td><p>4,519</p></td><td><p>22,632</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>7,085</p></td><td><p>25,577</p></td><td><p>4,853</p></td><td><p>20,419</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>7,000</p></td><td><p>17,466</p></td><td><p>4,478</p></td><td><p>12,591</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><em>Source:</em> Hospital Episode Statistics, NHS Digital</p><p><em>Notes: </em></p><ol><li>A&amp;E diagnosis - psychiatric condition - Please note that the recording of the diagnosis field within the A&amp;E data set is not mandatory. It is not known to what extent changes over time are as a result of improvements in recording practice. The diagnosis codes used are:</li></ol><p>35 = Psychiatric conditions.</p><ol start="2"><li>A&amp;E patient group - deliberate self-harm - The A&amp;E patient group records the reason for an A&amp;E episode. The A&amp;E patient group codes used are:</li></ol><p>30 = Deliberate self-harm</p><ol start="3"><li>Re-attendances within the year – Re-attendances are counted when they occur within the same financial year as the attendance that preceded it.</li></ol>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-11-14T17:44:10.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631152/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631152/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631152/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-07","Accident and Emergency Departments: Mental Illness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many people who attended accident and emergency (A&E) (a) with a primary diagnosis of a mental health condition or (b) due to intentional self-harm were re-admitted to A&E (i) within seven days or (ii) in any other timeframe in each of the last six years.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","51975"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631153","Department of Health","false","2016-11-14","<p>This information is not held centrally.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood","51972","2016-11-14T15:14:07.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631153/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631153/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631153/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-07","Accident and Emergency Departments: Alcoholic Drinks and Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many people who attended accident and emergency (A&E) with conditions relating to drugs and alcohol use were re-admitted to A&E (a) within seven days or (b) in any other timeframe in each of the last six years.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","51976"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631154","Cabinet Office","false","2016-11-14","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2016-11-14T14:14:04.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631154/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631154/answer","PQ51980 v.02 (1) (1).pdf","PQ51980 v.02 (1) (1).pdf","UKSA Response to PQ 51980","UKSA Response to PQ 51980","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631154/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-11-07","Drugs: Overdoses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many people have died as a result of a drug overdose in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","51980"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631155","Department of Health","false","2016-11-18","<p>It is not the role of the Department to collect data on the cost of sickness absence to the National Health Service due to hip arthroscopy and other medical treatments not being provided by clinical commissioning groups.</p><p> </p><p>The Department keeps NHS data collection requirements to a minimum, enabling trusts to concentrate their resources on improving the health and wellbeing of their staff and patients.</p><p> </p><p>Trusts, which are responsible for managing their staff sickness absence costs, should maintain comprehensive sickness absence records and, as indicated in my answer of 4 November to Question <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-questions-answers/?page=1&amp;max=20&amp;questiontype=AllQuestions&amp;house=commons%2clords&amp;uin=50657" target="_blank">50657</a>, from this information, tailor the health and wellbeing support they provide their workforce to meet staff needs and help keep them at work.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-11-18T09:29:32.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631155/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631155/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631155/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-07","NHS: Sick Leave","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to his Answer of 4 November 2016 to Question 50657, if his Department will collect centrally information on the cost of staff sickness to the NHS due to (a) hip arthroscopy and (b) other medical treatments not being provided by clinical commissioning groups.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","51996"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631156","Department of Health","false","2016-11-14","<p>The Department does not hold information on these meetings centrally. It is for individual trusts and foundation trusts to manage regular and extraordinary meetings as appropriate for their organisation.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-11-14T16:30:29.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631156/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631156/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631156/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-07","NHS Trusts: Governing Bodies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, for each hospital trust in England, when that trust's governing body's regular or extraordinary meetings took place in the last six months; and whether each such meeting included a confidential section from which Healthwatch or the general public were excluded.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","51997"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631157","Department of Health","false","2016-11-14","<p>The information requested is in the attached table.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-11-14T16:44:33.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631157/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631157/answer","Table for PQ51965.xlsx","Table for PQ51965.xlsx","PQ51965 table","PQ51965 table","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631157/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-07","Pregnancy: Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many perinatal mental health admissions there were in (a) Liverpool Wavertree constituency, (b) Liverpool, (c) England and (d) each region and constituent part of the UK in each year since 2009-10.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","51965"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631158","Department of Health","false","2016-11-14","<p>The number and location of mother and baby units (MBUs) opened since 2010, as supplied by NHS England, are as follows:</p><p> </p><p>Rainbow Mother and Baby Unit, Chelmsford (new unit opened 2013) 5 beds</p><p> </p><p>Florence House Mother and Baby Unit, Bournemouth (new unit opened 2013) 5 beds</p><p> </p><p>Work is also underway to increase the number of beds in existing MBUs (that have the capacity to expand) and to create three new MBUs in areas where there is currently no provision. These areas are the South West, the East of England and the North West.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-11-14T15:18:59.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631158/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631158/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631158/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-07","Pregnancy: Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, which in-patient mother and baby units that specialise in caring for women during the perinatal period have opened since 2010; where such units are situated; when such units opened; and how many beds each such unit has.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","51966"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631159","Department of Health","false","2016-11-14","<p>Clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) are required to increase their spend on mental health services by a greater amount than the growth in their allocation. A requirement to meet this mental health investment standard is included within the NHS Operational Planning and Contracting Guidance 2017 – 2019.</p><p> </p><p>Where a commissioner fails to invest in mental health services in line with its plan without providing adequate justification, NHS England can consider imposing directions on the CCG to increase its level of investment. To assist with this performance assessment, NHS England is embedding other data collections to help identify outcomes and prevalence indicators that can be monitored alongside financial investment levels and give a more balanced picture of mental health service commissioning. The NHS England Mental Health Five Year Forward View Dashboard will report against spend on mental health services.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood","51968","2016-11-14T16:41:16.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631159/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631159/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631159/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-07","Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to the Mental Health Five Year Forward View Dashboard, what criteria clinical commissioning groups have to meet in order to give a positive answer to the indicator on parity of esteem achieved in 2016-17 planned spend.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","51967"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631160","Department of Health","false","2016-11-14","<p>Clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) are required to increase their spend on mental health services by a greater amount than the growth in their allocation. A requirement to meet this mental health investment standard is included within the NHS Operational Planning and Contracting Guidance 2017 – 2019.</p><p> </p><p>Where a commissioner fails to invest in mental health services in line with its plan without providing adequate justification, NHS England can consider imposing directions on the CCG to increase its level of investment. To assist with this performance assessment, NHS England is embedding other data collections to help identify outcomes and prevalence indicators that can be monitored alongside financial investment levels and give a more balanced picture of mental health service commissioning. The NHS England Mental Health Five Year Forward View Dashboard will report against spend on mental health services.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood","51967","2016-11-14T16:41:16.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631160/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631160/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631160/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-07","Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to the Mental Health Five Year Forward View Dashboard, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that clinical commissioning groups which do not give a positive answer to the indicator on parity of esteem achieved in 2016-17 planned spend make progress on achieving such parity of esteem as soon as practicable.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","51968"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631161","Department of Health","false","2016-11-14","<p>The number of perinatal mental health specialist midwives is not collected.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-11-14T09:50:26.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631161/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631161/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631161/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-07","Pregnancy: Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many perinatal mental health specialist midwives were active in (a) Liverpool Wavertree constituency, (b) Liverpool, (c) England and (d) each region and constituent part of the UK in each year since 2009-10.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","51969"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631162","Department of Health","false","2016-11-14","<p>The provision of accident and emergency services at the Royal Blackburn Hospital, and the Royal Preston Hospital, are matters for the local National Health Service.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-11-14T16:28:26.923Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631162/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631162/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631162/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-07","Accident and Emergency Departments: Lancashire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether his Department plans to help protect from closure the accident and emergency departments of Blackburn and Preston hospitals.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","51970"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631163","Department of Health","false","2016-11-14","<p>There have been no recent discussions between the Department and clinical bodies on the use of 3D printer technology on people with fractures.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-11-14T16:34:37.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631163/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631163/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631163/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-07","Fractures: Digital Technology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what discussions his Department has had with clinical bodies on the use of 3D printer technology on people with fractures.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","52091"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631164","Department of Health","false","2016-11-17","<p>The Government is committed to improving access to general practitioner (GP) services as part of our plan for a seven day National Health Service. By 2020, everyone will be able to access routine GP appointments at evenings and weekends, as part of the Government’s commitment to a seven day NHS.</p><p> </p><p>On 21 April 2016, NHS England published the GP Forward View, a package of support to help get general practice back on its feet, improve patient care and access, and invest in new ways of providing primary care. The GP Forward View sets out that we are investing an extra £2.4 billion a year for general practice services by 2020/21 – this represents a 14% increase in real terms. The overall investment for general practice includes a £500 million national 'turnaround' package to support GP practices.</p><p> </p><p>A part of the GP Forward View, there are plans to double the rate of growth of the medical workforce to create an extra 5,000 additional doctors working in general practice by 2020. This will include increasing GP training recruitment, a major national and international recruitment campaign, bursaries and post-certificate of completion of training fellowships in hard to recruit areas, and encouraging GPs back into general practice.</p><p> </p><p>There is also a commitment to a minimum of 5,000 other staff working in general practice by 2020/21. This will include investment in an extra 3,000 mental health therapists and investment to pilot and then extend clinical pharmacists in practices. There will be investment in a general practice nurse development strategy and to support the training of reception and clerical staff, practice manager development and multi-disciplinary training hubs. In addition there will be introduction of a new Pharmacy Integration Fund, pilots of new medical assistant roles to support doctors and investment by Health Education England in the training of 1,000 physician associates to support general practice.</p><p> </p><p>There will be a major £30 million ‘Releasing Time for Patients’ development programme to help release capacity within general practice.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-11-17T11:44:55.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631164/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631164/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631164/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-07","General Practitioners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department is taking to increase the (a) number and (b) accessibility of practising GPs.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","52092"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631165","Department of Health","false","2016-11-14","<p>From April to August 2016, which are the only months in this financial year for which we have data, an additional £4.5 million in prescription charge income was collected as a result of the increase in the single charge to £8.40.</p><p> </p><p>Prescription prepayment certificates also raise revenue for the National Health Service. These save money for those who need many items and who are not otherwise exempt. The cost of prescription prepayment certificates was frozen this year, to protect those with the greatest need.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-11-14T16:13:06.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631165/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631165/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631165/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-07","Prescriptions: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much additional revenue has been generated since prescription charges rose in England on 1 April 2016.","false","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson","52062"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631166","Department of Health","false","2016-11-17","<p>The Department has had no discussions with clinical bodies on the use of cider vinegar to prevent strokes, nor on the potential connection between chronic snoring and cardiac arrest.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat","52082","2016-11-17T11:49:26.023Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631166/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631166/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631166/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-07","Strokes: Vinegar","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what discussions his Department has had with clinical bodies on the use of cider vinegar to reduce the risk of strokes.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","52089"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631167","Department of Health","false","2016-11-14","<p>NHS Choices is the main source of guidance on vitamins and minerals and carries a special report from 2011 on supplements. This gives clear information about the risks of over-consumption.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-11-14T15:25:20.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631167/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631167/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631167/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-07","Vitamins: Health Hazards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what guidance his Department makes available on the risks of over-consumption of vitamin supplements.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","52090"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631168","Department of Health","false","2016-11-16","<p>The proposals developed by the north, east and west Devon Success Regime have drawn upon a range of evidence, including studies of the potential benefits of care closer to home. This included a number of national and local studies, such as the Torrington Community Care Test of Change in Social Care which can be found at:</p><p><a href="http://www.northdevonhealth.nhs.uk/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/Appendix-7-Evidence-Review.pdf" target="_blank">www.northdevonhealth.nhs.uk/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/Appendix-7-Evidence-Review.pdf</a></p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-11-16T09:46:44.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631168/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631168/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631168/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-07","Health Services: Devon","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what scientific evidence led to the promotion of the care closer to home model adopted by the north, east and west Devon Success Regime.","false","Biography information for Mr Geoffrey Cox","Torridge and West Devon","Mr Geoffrey Cox","52024"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631169","Department of Health","false","2016-11-14","<p>The National Health Service list prices of licensed branded medicines are controlled by either the voluntary 2014 Pharmaceutical Price Regulation Scheme (PPRS) or the statutory scheme. Companies in the PPRS are not required to routinely provide such information when launching new medicines. However, the Department may request actual and forecast information relating to the United Kingdom market under these cost headings if it is deemed necessary to reach an agreement on price. Under the statutory scheme, the Secretary of State may have regard to, among other things, the cost of research into, and development of, the product for which a price is requested.</p><p> </p><p>All pharmaceutical companies are required to provide actual and forecast information for these cost headings if requesting a price increase on an existing medicine.</p><p> </p><p>The Department does not control the selling price of generic medicines; instead it relies on competition and the retained margin incentive for dispensing contractors to drive down prices, therefore this information is not required from manufacturers before placing a generic product on the market.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-11-14T16:36:37.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631169/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631169/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631169/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-07","NHS: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what information on the costs of (a) research and development, (b) marketing and (c) distribution his Department requires when negotiating the price of medicines.","false","Biography information for Mr Virendra Sharma","Ealing, Southall","Mr Virendra Sharma","52021"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631170","Department of Health","false","2016-11-18","<p>Based on the latest internationally comparable Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) data, total health spending in the United Kingdom, as set out by the OECD for 2014 (published 30 June 2016), and which includes public (Government) and private spend, is at 9.9% of Gross Domestic Product (GDP), above the OECD average1 of 9.0% and the EU-15 average of 9.8%.</p><p> </p><p>Reducing health spending inequalities is part of the core formula that is used to determine the funding that is allocated to clinical commissioning groups (CCGs), which are the equivalent of UK health authority districts in England. Responsibility for CCG allocations rests with NHS England. NHS England also has a duty to reduce health inequalities.</p><p> </p><p>The formula includes an adjustment for unmet need and health inequalities, which has been refined for 2016-17 to 2020-21 allocations.</p><p> </p><p>The unmet need and health inequalities adjustment continues to be based on the standardised mortality ratio for those aged under 75 years. The latest data has been used and the adjustment refined to give a higher weight per head to the areas with the worst standardised mortality ratio for those aged under 75 years and to be based on the size of each CCG’s registered lists in place of Office for National Statistics populations, on which it was previously based.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>NHS England has published a technical guide to allocations which sets out all the individual factors used in determining the allocation levels. The guide is available here:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/2016/04/allocations-tech-guide-16-17/" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/2016/04/allocations-tech-guide-16-17/#</a></p><p> </p><p>Funding for other parts of the UK is a matter for the devolved administrations.</p><p> </p><p><em>Note</em>:</p><p><sup>1</sup>The reported averages reflect the simple average of countries’ figures without weighting that for population or GDP of the respective countries.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-11-18T10:59:21.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631170/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631170/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631170/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-07","Health Services: Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he has taken to reduce health spending inequalities between (a) the UK and other European countries and (b) UK health authority districts.","false","Biography information for Mr Geoffrey Cox","Torridge and West Devon","Mr Geoffrey Cox","52023"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631171","Department of Health","false","2016-11-17","<p>Working with local National Health Service organisations, Health Education England produces an annual National Workforce Plan for England, which sets out future training requirements for the NHS.</p><p> </p><p>At a local level, it is the responsibility of NHS organisations to ensure that their staff, through Continuing Professional Development, have the ongoing skills required to deliver safe and effective care to patients.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-11-17T11:59:28.123Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631171/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631171/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631171/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-07","NHS: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of skills shortages within the NHS.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","52157"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631172","Department of Health","false","2016-11-17","<p>Our ambition is for everyone approaching the end of life to receive high quality care that reflects their individual needs, choices and preferences.</p><p> </p><p>On 5 July, we set out our plans to improve end of life care in the Government response to the independent Review of Choice in End of Life Care, including a commitment to develop and document a personalised care plan, based on what matters to you and your needs and preferences, including any advance decisions and your views about where you want to be cared for and where you want to die, and to review and revise this plan throughout the duration of your illness.</p><p> </p><p>To support delivery, NHS England is working with two New Care Model sites of Airedale and Southend to test an innovative approach to ‘serious illness conversations’ in which clinicians are trained to support people with serious illnesses to discuss what is important to them, treating these discussions as a clinical intervention which delivers patient-centred care. NHS England has also commissioned the National Council for Palliative Care (NCPC) to develop an educational film to prepare people with advanced diseases and long term conditions for consultations with clinicians, which will be released in November.</p><p> </p><p>The Department and NHS England are working with voluntary sector partners to raise general public awareness of issues around death and dying and the importance of Advance Care Planning. The Department and NHS England support the Dying Matters Coalition, which promotes a national conversation around death and dying. NHS England will also lead a public facing campaign to promote choice and personalisation in end of life care which will be supported by voluntary sector partners, in particular the NCPC, who have been commissioned to lead a piece of work promoting the benefits of Advance Care Planning and the sharing of these records with relevant professionals.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-11-17T11:50:25.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631172/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631172/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631172/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-07","Palliative Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what recent steps his Department has taken to encourage at risk patients to consider advanced planning of end of life care.","false","Biography information for Karen Lumley","Redditch","Karen Lumley","52114"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631173","Department of Health","false","2016-11-14","<p>The United Kingdom is providing support to low and middle income countries both through direct country support to a select number of countries and through producing training and guidance that will be available to all low and middle income countries. Country projects will be delivered through our delivery partners the World Health Organization Framework Convention for Tobacco Control secretariat and the United Nations development programme.</p><p> </p><p>Robust monitoring and evaluation mechanisms have been put in place to ensure the project delivers maximum value for the British taxpayer.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-11-14T17:38:09.033Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631173/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631173/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631173/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-07","WHO Framework Convention on Tobacco Control","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to his Answer of 24 October 2016 to Question 49531, on World Health Organisation framework convention of tobacco control, what the nature is of the support being offered to other countries; and which countries have accepted that support.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","52127"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631174","Department of Health","false","2016-11-14","<p>NHS Digital publishes Hospital and Community Health Services data on the number of mental health nurses employed in the National Health Service in England.</p><p>The data for the number of mental health nurses employed in the NHS trusts in Southwark as at 31 July 2016 are available via the following weblink:</p><p><a href="http://content.digital.nhs.uk/media/22896/Qualified-mental-health-nurses-in-specified-NHS-Trusts-in-Southwark---July-2016/xls/Qualified_mental_health_nurses_in_specified_NHS_Trusts_in_Southwark_-_July_2016.xlsx" target="_blank">http://content.digital.nhs.uk/media/22896/Qualified-mental-health-nurses-in-specified-NHS-Trusts-in-Southwark---July-2016/xls/Qualified_mental_health_nurses_in_specified_NHS_Trusts_in_Southwark_-_July_2016.xlsx</a></p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-11-14T15:17:37.303Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631174/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631174/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631174/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-07","Mental Health Services: Nurses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many mental health nurses there are employed by the local NHS trust in Southwark.","false","Biography information for Ms Harriet Harman","Camberwell and Peckham","Ms Harriet Harman","52134"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631175","Department of Health","false","2016-11-17","<p>The Government is committed to improving access to general practitioner (GP) services. Additional funding of over £500 million by 2020/21 will provide extra capacity across England, meaning that by 2020, everyone will have access to GP appointments, including sufficient routine GP appointments, at evenings and weekends to meet locally determined demand, alongside effective access to other primary care and GP services such as urgent care services.</p><p> </p><p>On 21 April 2016, NHS England published the General Practice Forward View, a package of support to help get general practice back on its feet, improve patient care and access, and invest in new ways of providing primary care. The General Practice Forward View sets out that we are investing a minimum extra £2.4 billion a year for general practice services by 2020/21 – this represents a 14% increase in real terms. The overall investment for general practice includes a one off sustainability and transformation package of £500 million national 'turnaround' package to support GP practices over five years.</p><p> </p><p>As part of the General Practice Forward View, there are plans to grow the medical workforce to create an extra 5,000 additional doctors working in general practice by 2020/21. This will include increasing general practitioner training recruitment, a major national and international recruitment campaign, bursaries and post-certificate of completion of training fellowships in hard to recruit areas, and encouraging GPs back into general practice.</p><p> </p><p>There is also a commitment to a minimum of 5,000 other staff working in general practice by 2020/21. This will include investment in an extra 3,000 mental health therapists for long-term physical conditions and investment to pilot and then extend clinical pharmacists in NHS111 hubs. There will be £15 million investment in a general practice nurse development strategy and to support the training of reception and clerical staff, practice manager development and multi-disciplinary training hubs. In addition there will be introduction of a new Pharmacy Integration Fund, pilots of new medical assistant roles to support doctors and investment by Health Education England in the training of 1,000 physician associates to support general practice.</p><p> </p><p>There will also be a major £30 million ‘Releasing Time for Patients’ development programme to help release capacity within general practice.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-11-17T11:46:19.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631175/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631175/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631175/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-07","General Practitioners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what recent steps his Department has taken to increase the amount of face time between GPs and patients.","false","Biography information for Karen Lumley","Redditch","Karen Lumley","52112"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631176","Cabinet Office","false","2016-11-15","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2016-11-15T09:41:15.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631176/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631176/answer","PQ52079 (1).pdf","PQ52079 (1).pdf","UKSA Letter to Member - Cancer","UKSA Letter to Member - Cancer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631176/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-11-07","Cancer: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many children have been diagnosed with cancer in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","52079"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631177","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-11-14","<p>We recognise the importance of tackling childhood obesity, which is caused by a number of complex factors. The Childhood Obesity Plan for Action, published in August, considered a number of different policy responses to address this problem. Additional advertising restrictions were considered as part of this process, but current restrictions in the UK are amongst the toughest in the world and the plan focuses on those areas which experts tell us are most effective.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2016-11-14T17:25:59.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631177/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631177/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631177/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-11-07","Obesity: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps the Government is taking to monitor the level of advertising for (a) breakfast cereals and (b) convenience foods for its effect on childhood obesity.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","52081"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631178","Department of Health","false","2016-11-14","<p>For unbranded generic medicines the Department relies on competition in the market to keep prices down. Prices therefore reflect supply and demand and differ from one day to the other, from customer to customer and are volume dependant. Therefore, no such assessment has been made.</p><p> </p><p>Branded medicines are the subject of price control under the Pharmaceutical Price Regulation Scheme (PPRS) and statutory scheme. Except in exceptional circumstances, the Department does not allow increases to the National Health Service list price under these schemes. Where price increases were agreed under the PPRS, the Department’s best estimate of additional cost was approximately £550,000 in 2015.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-11-14T15:23:21.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631178/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631178/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631178/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-07","NHS: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what recent assessment his Department has made of the effect on the level of the NHS budget of changes in the prices of drugs.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","52080"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631179","Department of Health","false","2016-11-17","<p>The Department has had no discussions with clinical bodies on the use of cider vinegar to prevent strokes, nor on the potential connection between chronic snoring and cardiac arrest.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat","52089","2016-11-17T11:49:26.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631179/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631179/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631179/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-07","Heart Diseases: Snoring","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what discussions his Department has had with clinical bodies on the potential connection between chronic snoring and incidences of cardiac arrest.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","52082"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631180","Department of Health","false","2016-11-14","<p>An ageing population and increasing multimorbidity means both prevalence of long term conditions and the associated treatment costs to the National Health Service are expected to increase. The analysis and forecasts produced as part of the Department’s Long Term Condition Compendium of Information, published in 2012, are the most recent estimates in this area.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-11-14T16:13:52.093Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631180/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631180/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631180/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-07","Diseases: Medical Treatments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 4 November 2016 to Question 51408, what estimate he has made of the potential increase in costs associated with long-term conditions for each year between 2016 and 2035.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","52106"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631181","Department of Health","false","2016-11-14","<p>The Exon skipping therapy eteplirsen (Exondys 51) is currently being considered for referral to the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence’s (NICE) highly specialised technologies (HST) programme. Following discussion between NICE, NHS England and the Department as part of the topic selection process, NICE recently consulted stakeholders on its suitability for the HST process.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-11-14T16:35:32.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631181/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631181/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631181/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-07","Muscular Dystrophy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what discussions his Department has had with NICE on a possible timetable for making Exon skipping therapy available to address Duchenne muscular dystrophy.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","52083"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631182","Department of Health","false","2016-11-14","<p>The vast majority of income and costs of National Health Service budgets are denominated in pounds sterling. There are a number of reasons for changes in NHS costs, and, as ever, specifically identifying the impact of exchange rate changes is not routinely undertaken.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","52197","2016-11-14T16:29:30.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631182/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631182/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631182/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-07","NHS: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the effect on NHS inflation of recent changes in the currency exchange rate.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","52196"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631183","Department of Health","false","2016-11-14","<p>The vast majority of income and costs of National Health Service budgets are denominated in pounds sterling. There are a number of reasons for changes in NHS costs, and, as ever, specifically identifying the impact of exchange rate changes is not routinely undertaken.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","52196","2016-11-14T16:29:30.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631183/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631183/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631183/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-07","NHS: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the effect on NHS finances of recent changes in the currency exchange rate.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","52197"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631184","Department of Health","false","2016-11-18","<p>The Department does not have a dedicated three to five strategy for supporting the training and development of advanced paediatric and neonatal nurse practitioners.</p><p> </p><p>It is Health Education England’s (HEE) responsibility to ensure that there is sufficient future supply of staff, including those needed in specialist fields such as this, to meet the workforce requirements of the English health system.</p><p> </p><p>As part of its ongoing work HEE continually looks to ensure that staff groups, such as those highlighted, have the correct planned workforce growth, consider whether new roles are required and ensure that existing undergraduate training and education meets the needs of both students and patients.</p><p> </p><p>At a local level, it is the responsibility of National Health Service organisations to ensure that their staff, through Continuing Professional Development, have the ongoing skills required to deliver safe and effective care to patients.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-11-18T10:47:47.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631184/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631184/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631184/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-07","Nurses: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what his Department's national three-to-five strategy is for supporting the training and development of advanced paediatric and neonatal nurse practitioners, to enable skilled acute care for infants, children and young people close to home.","false","Biography information for Jeremy Lefroy","Stafford","Jeremy Lefroy","52185"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631185","Department of Health","false","2016-11-14","<p>The criteria used to establish the baseline spend for the minimum investment in mental health calculation is the previous year’s spend on mental health. The NHS England Mental Health Five Year Forward View Dashboard will report against spend on mental health services.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-11-14T15:27:48.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631185/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631185/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631185/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-07","Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to the Mental Health Five Year Forward View Dashboard, what criteria his Department used to establish the baseline for year-on-year comparative figures in the parity of esteem indicator.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","52199"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631186","Department of Health","false","2016-11-14","<p>We welcome the Centre for Mental Health and the Howard League’s report and are committed to reducing the number of self-inflicted deaths in prisons. It is important that our work is informed by the views of prisoners and this report is informing the work that the National Offender Management Service (NOMS) is taking forward in partnership with NHS England and Public Health England (PHE) to reduce self-inflicted deaths and self-harm.</p><p> </p><p>NOMS, PHE and NHS England are taking forward collaborative evidence-based action to reduce self-inflicted deaths in prison. PHE has supported this work by providing evidence and expertise on suicide prevention and how to apply this in prison environments. This includes education and training for prison officers; identification of ‘high risk’ prisoners and high risk situations; improving the environment in prisons including ‘purposeful activity’ and a whole prison approach to health improvement generally. These actions correspond to many of the key recommendations in the Centre for Mental Health and the Howard League’s report.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-11-14T15:31:07.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631186/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631186/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631186/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-07","Mental Health: Prisoners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the implications for his policy are of the Centre for Mental Health and the Howard League's report Preventing Prison Suicide: Perspectives from the inside; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","52200"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631187","Department of Health","false","2016-11-14","<p>The data is not available in the format requested.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-11-14T15:24:19.81Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631187/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631187/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631187/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-07","Secure Psychiatric Units","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the (a) proportion and (b) number of people is in secure mental health units in England who are clinically ready to be discharged but are still in a unit; and in each case, what the reasons are for the delay in discharge of such people in the latest period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","52201"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631188","Home Office","false","2016-11-18","<p>Whilst the Home Office fully supports the police exploiting technology to help cut crime wherever possible, the assessment of the effectiveness of body-worn cameras in a) capturing evidence leading to successful prosecution and (b) preventing unwarranted charges being brought against police officers is an operational consideration for policing.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-11-18T13:31:38.123Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631188/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631188/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631188/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-07","Police: Cameras","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the effectiveness of police body-worn cameras in (a) capturing evidence leading to successful prosecution and (b) preventing unwarranted charges being brought against police officers.","false","Biography information for Karen Lumley","Redditch","Karen Lumley","52174"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631189","Home Office","false","2016-11-17","<p>The Government is committed to tackling all forms of domestic violence, and supporting all victims. The Government has provided over £30 million of funding for domestic and sexual abuse victims over the last three years. The majority of these services have been commissioned on the basis that the needs of all victims are met.</p><p>The Home Office has specifically funded the Men’s Advice Line, which provides support and advice to male victims of domestic violence and the national lesbian, gay, bisexual and transgender domestic abuse helpline over the last three years.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2016-11-17T17:01:32.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631189/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631189/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631189/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-07","Domestic Abuse: Males","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how much her Department has spent to support male victims of domestic abuse in each of the last three years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Sir Alan Campbell","Tynemouth","Mr Alan Campbell","52198"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631190","Home Office","false","2016-11-21","<p>Home Office Ministers have regular meetings with Ministerial colleagues and others as part of the process of policy development and delivery. As was the case with previous administrations, it is not the Government's practice to provide details of all such meetings.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-11-21T18:19:42.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631190/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631190/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631190/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-07","Refugees: Syria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what recent meetings have been held between Ministers and their counterparts in the Welsh Government on plans for Syrian resettlement in Wales; and if the Government plans to publish the minutes of such meetings.","false","Biography information for Ann Clwyd","Cynon Valley","Ann Clwyd","52175"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631191","Home Office","false","2016-11-14","<p>This is a voluntary scheme whereby local authorities sign up to accept refugees on a voluntary basis. We have asked authorities to think very carefully to ensure they have the infrastructure and support networks needed to deliver the appropriate care and integration of these refugees they plan to resettle. The number of people resettled in a particular period will depend on a range of factors. This includes the number of referrals we have received from the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees and the number of confirmed places we have received from local authorities that are suitable for the specific needs of those who have been accepted for resettlement. Progress on resettlement will be reported in quarterly immigration statistics.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-11-14T16:08:13.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631191/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631191/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631191/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-07","Refugees: Syria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate she has made of how many Syrian refugees are planned to be located in each local authority area in Wales under the Syrian vulnerable persons resettlement programme in 2017.","false","Biography information for Ann Clwyd","Cynon Valley","Ann Clwyd","52173"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631192","Home Office","false","2016-11-14","<p>Progress on resettlement in each local authority is indicated in quarterly immigration statistics. The last set of statistics, published on 25 August 2016 showed that 2,646 Syrians were relocated to the UK under the Syrian Vulnerable Persons Resettlement scheme between October 2015 and June 2016 and sets out how many were located in each local authority.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-11-14T15:44:18.093Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631192/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631192/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631192/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-07","Refugees: Syria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many Syrian refugees located in each local authority in Wales have been resettled under the Syrian vulnerable persons resettlement programme.","false","Biography information for Ann Clwyd","Cynon Valley","Ann Clwyd","52172"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631193","Home Office","false","2016-11-18","<p>Whilst the Home Office fully supports the police exploiting technology to help cut crime wherever possible, the assessment of the effectiveness of body-worn cameras in preventing harassment and abuse of police officers is an operational consideration for policing.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-11-18T13:32:00.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631193/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631193/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631193/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-07","Police: Cameras","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the effectiveness of body-worn cameras in preventing harassment and abuse of police officers.","false","Biography information for Karen Lumley","Redditch","Karen Lumley","52167"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631194","Home Office","false","2016-12-14","<p>The Home Office does not maintain records of firearms seized by police forces in England and Wales. The National Ballistics Intelligence Service regularly assesses the volume and type of illegal firearms in use in the UK.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-12-14T13:10:50.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631194/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631194/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631194/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-07","Firearms: Seized Articles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many illegal firearms have been seized in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","52084"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631195","Home Office","false","2016-11-14","<p>All PBS tier 4 applications are subject to assessment against paragraph 245ZV(k) of the immigration rules which state the Entry Clearance Officer must be satisfied the applicant is a genuine student.</p><p>Entry Clearance Officers have access to detailed guidance on how the Genuine Student Rule should be implemented with reference to the relevant sections of the immigrations rules, and guidance when interviewing may be required to support decision making.</p><p>Entry Clearance Managers will conduct regular reviews on the Tier 4 decision making process and UKVI International have a specialist assurance function that reviews decision quality of PBS applications.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-11-14T16:08:52.293Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631195/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631195/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631195/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-07","Visas: Overseas Students","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what recent assessment she has made of the consistency of applications of the provisions in the immigration rules on the genuine student rule.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","52095"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631196","Home Office","false","2016-11-21","<p>While the UK remains in the EU, EU national university staff and students will continue to have the same rights and status that they had before the referendum. The Prime Minister has been clear that she wants to protect the status of EU nationals already living and working in the UK after the UK leaves the EU, and the only circumstances in which that would not be possible is if British citizens' rights in other EU Member States were not protected in return.</p><p>The Government has provided repeated assurances on this point. It has also been clear that the timeframe for resolving this issue is through an agreement with the EU to ensure fair treatment of British citizens living in other EU countries.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-11-21T18:26:02.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631196/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631196/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631196/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-07","Immigration: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will grant existing EU national university staff and students leave to remain in the UK in advance of Article 50 being triggered.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","52122"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631197","Home Office","false","2016-11-14","<p>The UK Government regularly shares intelligence and cooperates with our international partners to monitor and counter displacement from Calais.</p><p>The UK is working extensively with international partners to tackle the people smuggling gangs who may facilitate displacement to other ports. In November 2015 the then Immigration Minister signed a joint declaration with Dutch and Belgian ministers to strengthen our joint response to the threat from organised immigration crime at northern European ports. More widely, the UK has established an Organised Immigration Taskforce that is exploiting opportunities in Europe and Africa to disrupt the crime groups involved.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-11-14T15:41:29.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631197/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631197/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631197/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-07","Migrant Camps: Calais","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to her oral statement on Calais of 24 October 2016, Official Report, columns 64-5, what discussions she has had with her (a) Belgian, (b) Dutch, (c) German and (d) Danish counterparts on ensuring that the closure of the Calais camp does not result in the displacement of migrants and refugees to ports in Belgium, Netherlands, Germany and Denmark.","false","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson","52138"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631198","House of Commons Commission","false","2016-11-15","<p>The percentage of people working for the House Service who have declared a disability is 3%. We do not report on what type of disability people declare.</p><p>The House has a track record of working with organisations who support adults with learning disabilities to secure paid employment or work experience with us. This includes through the Speaker’s Parliamentary Placement Scheme, the House of Commons Apprenticeship Scheme, and participating – with ParliAble – in Inclusive Employers and Mencap’s Learning Disabilities Work Experience Week, as well as through standard recruitment and selection practices.</p><p>The House of Commons is a Partner of the Business Disability Forum. This year we participated in the BDF’s Disability Standard, which measures organisations against 10 criteria, including recruitment and adjustments. We improved our score of 42% in 2013 to 83%, achieving Silver accreditation.</p>","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake",,"2016-11-15T17:30:26.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631198/answer","Biography information for Tom Brake","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631198/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631198/answer",,,,,"18","House of Commons Commission","House of Commons Commission","2016-11-07","House of Commons: Learning Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Rt. hon. Member for Carshalton and Wallington representing the House of Commons Commission, how many people in the House of Commons Service have learning disabilities.","false","Biography information for Kevin Hollinrake","Thirsk and Malton","Kevin Hollinrake","52009"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631199","Department for International Development","false","2016-11-14","<p>The table below shows the percentage of total UK Official Development Assistance delivered by the aid agencies of other countries for each of the past five years.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Proportion of Total UK ODA</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>0.7%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>0.6%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>1.4%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>1.3%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>1.3%</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-11-14T17:57:06.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631199/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631199/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631199/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-11-07","Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what proportion of UK aid was delivered by the aid agencies of other countries in (a) the most recent period for which figures are available and (b) each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","52034"
